 Now, richer parents could send their kids to private schools, many of which stayed open,

1:38:44.160 --> 1:38:45.160
 even in the blue states.

1:38:45.160 --> 1:38:46.160
 They could get pods.

1:38:46.160 --> 1:38:47.160
 They could get tutors.

1:38:47.160 --> 1:38:52.320
 That's not true for poorer and middle class parents.

1:38:52.320 --> 1:38:56.160
 As a result, what we did is we took away life opportunities for kids.

1:38:56.160 --> 1:39:03.660
 We tried to teach five year olds to read via Zoom in kindergarten.

1:39:03.660 --> 1:39:07.200
 The consequence actually, you think, okay, we can just make it up, but it's really difficult

1:39:07.200 --> 1:39:09.240
 to make that up.

1:39:09.240 --> 1:39:16.720
 There's a literature in health economics that shows that even relatively small disruptions

1:39:16.720 --> 1:39:22.720
 in schooling can have lifelong consequences, negative consequences for kids.

1:39:22.720 --> 1:39:30.400
 They end up growing up poorer, they lead shorter lives and less healthy lives as a consequence.

1:39:30.400 --> 1:39:34.880
 That's what the literature now shows is likely to happen with the interruptions of schooling

1:39:34.880 --> 1:39:36.880
 that we had in the United States.

1:39:36.880 --> 1:39:39.240
 Many European countries actually managed to avoid this.

1:39:39.240 --> 1:39:43.320
 There were in the early days, the epidemic, great indications that children first were

1:39:43.320 --> 1:39:49.400
 not severely at risk from COVID itself, nor are they super spreaders.

1:39:49.400 --> 1:39:52.000
 Schools were not the source of community spread.

1:39:52.000 --> 1:39:57.840
 Community spread the disease to schools, not the other way around.

1:39:57.840 --> 1:40:01.680
 We can talk about the scientific base of that if you'd like, but that was pretty well known

1:40:01.680 --> 1:40:04.640
 even in October.

1:40:04.640 --> 1:40:11.360
 We closed hospitals in order to keep them available to COVID patients, but as a result,

1:40:11.360 --> 1:40:14.280
 men skipped breast cancer screening.

1:40:14.280 --> 1:40:18.000
 As a result, they are showing up with late stage breast cancer that should have been

1:40:18.000 --> 1:40:19.880
 picked up last year.

1:40:19.880 --> 1:40:23.960
 Men and women skipped colon cancer screening, again, with later stage disease that should

1:40:23.960 --> 1:40:26.320
 have been picked up last year with earlier stage.

1:40:26.320 --> 1:40:31.880
 For patients with diabetes, it's very important to have regular screening for blood sugar

1:40:31.880 --> 1:40:38.440
 levels and sort of counseling for lifestyle improvement, and we skipped that.

1:40:38.440 --> 1:40:42.360
 People stayed home with heart attacks and died at home with heart attacks.

1:40:42.360 --> 1:40:52.080
 You had this wide range of medical and psychological harms that were being utterly ignored as a

1:40:52.080 --> 1:40:53.600
 result of the lockdowns.

1:40:53.600 --> 1:40:57.960
 Plus, there's the economic pain.

1:40:57.960 --> 1:41:04.120
 Like you said, the whatever is a good term for the nonlaptop class, people would lose

1:41:04.120 --> 1:41:05.120
 their jobs.

1:41:05.120 --> 1:41:10.560
 Yes, there might be in the Western world support for them financially, but the big

1:41:10.560 --> 1:41:17.960
 loss there that is perhaps correlated with the depression and suicide is loss of meaning,

1:41:17.960 --> 1:41:24.520
 loss of hope for the future, loss of a sense of stability, all the pride you have in being

1:41:24.520 --> 1:41:34.120
 able to make money that allows you to pave your own way in the world, and yes, just having

1:41:34.120 --> 1:41:38.080
 less money than you're used to, so your family, your kids are suffering, all those kinds of

1:41:38.080 --> 1:41:39.080
 things.

1:41:39.080 --> 1:41:43.640
 There's, again, an economics literature on this, on deaths of despair, it was called.

1:41:43.640 --> 1:41:45.960
 2009, there was the Great Recession.

1:41:45.960 --> 1:41:53.960
 It led to an enormous uptake in overdose from drugs, suicidality, depression as a result

1:41:53.960 --> 1:41:57.040
 of the job losses that happened during the Great Recession.

1:41:57.040 --> 1:42:04.080
 Well, that's happening again, like an enormous increase in drug overdoses.

1:42:04.080 --> 1:42:06.720
 That's not an accident.

1:42:06.720 --> 1:42:08.280
 That's a lockdown harm, right?

1:42:08.280 --> 1:42:10.520
 Same thing with the job losses.

1:42:10.520 --> 1:42:15.200
 The job losses, by the way, are like, it's so interesting because the states that stayed

1:42:15.200 --> 1:42:20.800
 open have had much, much lower unemployment than the states that stayed closed.

1:42:20.800 --> 1:42:23.640
 The labor force participation rates declined by 3%.

1:42:23.640 --> 1:42:28.680
 It's women that separated because they stayed home with their kids.

1:42:28.680 --> 1:42:37.160
 We've reversed a generation of women, improving women's participation in the labor force.

1:42:37.160 --> 1:42:43.800
 Do you think it has to do with the institutions that we mentioned that there was so much priority

1:42:43.800 --> 1:42:52.600
 given or so much power given to maybe NIH versus other civilian leaders, or do people

1:42:52.600 --> 1:42:54.440
 just not care about the economic pain?

1:42:54.440 --> 1:42:55.440
 The leaders.

1:42:55.440 --> 1:42:59.240
 Because to me, it was obvious.

1:42:59.240 --> 1:43:03.880
 I mean, probably it's just studying history.

1:43:03.880 --> 1:43:11.800
 Whenever I listened to people on Twitter, on mainstream news, or just anything, I realized

1:43:11.800 --> 1:43:14.640
 that's the very top.

1:43:14.640 --> 1:43:20.440
 The people that have a voice represent a tiny selection of people, and so whenever there's

1:43:20.440 --> 1:43:28.440
 hard times, I always kind of think about the quiet, the voiceless, the quiet suffering

1:43:28.440 --> 1:43:35.480
 of the tens of millions, of the hundreds of millions, to the political leaders not just

1:43:35.480 --> 1:43:36.480
 give a damn.

1:43:36.480 --> 1:43:41.360
 I mean, I think it was actually a very odd ethical thing at the beginning of the pandemic,

1:43:41.360 --> 1:43:47.680
 where if you brought up economic harms at all, you were seen as callous.

1:43:47.680 --> 1:43:51.920
 So I had a reporter call me up, almost at the very beginning of the epidemic, asking

1:43:51.920 --> 1:43:57.000
 me about a very particular phenomenon.

1:43:57.000 --> 1:44:01.800
 So he was anticipating a rise in child abuse, because children were going to be staying

1:44:01.800 --> 1:44:02.800
 at home.

1:44:02.800 --> 1:44:06.600
 Child abuse is generally picked up at school, and that actually happened.

1:44:06.600 --> 1:44:12.800
 The report to child abuse dropped, but actual child abuse increased, because normally you

1:44:12.800 --> 1:44:16.160
 pick up the child abuse at school and then you have the intervention, right?

1:44:16.160 --> 1:44:19.240
 So yeah, I started talking about like, well, there's going to be some economic harms, and

1:44:19.240 --> 1:44:21.880
 they're going to have health consequences, but the economic harms matter.

1:44:21.880 --> 1:44:28.320
 But he counseled me, and I think he had my best interest at heart, like if you were to

1:44:28.320 --> 1:44:35.360
 put that in the story, I would be, I'd essentially be canceled, because the narrative that arose

1:44:35.360 --> 1:44:41.840
 in March of 2020 is if you care about money at all, you're evil and crass, you must only

1:44:41.840 --> 1:44:43.960
 care about lives.

1:44:43.960 --> 1:44:49.040
 The problem with that narrative is that that money, which we're talking about, is actually

1:44:49.040 --> 1:44:51.680
 lives of poor people, right?

1:44:51.680 --> 1:44:57.720
 When you throw 100 million people around the world into poverty, you're going to see enormous

1:44:57.720 --> 1:45:01.360
 harm to their health, enormous increases in their mortality.

1:45:01.360 --> 1:45:06.240
 It is not immoral to think about that and worry about that in the context of this pandemic

1:45:06.240 --> 1:45:07.400
 response.

1:45:07.400 --> 1:45:12.440
 Our mind focused so much on COVID that it forgot that there are so many other public

1:45:12.440 --> 1:45:16.600
 health priorities as well that need our attention desperately.

1:45:16.600 --> 1:45:21.880
 This is the thing I sensed about San Francisco when I visited.

1:45:21.880 --> 1:45:24.720
 I was thinking of moving there for a startup.

1:45:24.720 --> 1:45:30.520
 This is the thing I'm really afraid of, especially if I have any effect on the world through

1:45:30.520 --> 1:45:34.640
 a startup, is losing touch in this kind of way.

1:45:34.640 --> 1:45:40.240
 That you mentioned the laptop class, living in this world where you're only concerned

1:45:40.240 --> 1:45:49.240
 about this particular class of people, and also, perhaps early on in the pandemic, amongst

1:45:49.240 --> 1:45:52.320
 the laptop class, there was a legitimate concern for health.

1:45:52.320 --> 1:45:56.120
 You're not sure how deadly this virus is.

1:45:56.120 --> 1:45:59.080
 You're not sure who to listen to, so there's a real concern.

1:45:59.080 --> 1:46:03.880
 Then at a certain point when the data starts coming in, you start becoming more and more

1:46:03.880 --> 1:46:05.160
 detached from the data.

1:46:05.160 --> 1:46:10.880
 You don't start caring less and less, and you start just swimming in the space of narratives,

1:46:10.880 --> 1:46:15.520
 like existing in the space of narratives, and you have this narrative in San Francisco,

1:46:15.520 --> 1:46:21.360
 in the laptop class, that you're just very proud that you know the truth.

1:46:21.360 --> 1:46:23.000
 You're the sole possessors of the truth.

1:46:23.000 --> 1:46:28.560
 You congratulate yourself on it, and you don't care what actually gigantic detrimental

1:46:28.560 --> 1:46:34.440
 effect it has on society, because you're mostly fine.

1:46:34.440 --> 1:46:36.680
 I'm so terrified of that.

1:46:36.680 --> 1:46:39.840
 Well, I think the answer to that is just to remember.

1:46:39.840 --> 1:46:40.840
 You remember.

1:46:40.840 --> 1:46:41.840
 Yeah.

1:46:41.840 --> 1:46:46.520
 I don't think, remember where you came from, and remember who you're doing this for.

1:46:46.520 --> 1:46:50.120
 The back of your head should always be, what's the purpose?

1:46:50.120 --> 1:46:51.120
 Why am I here?

1:46:51.120 --> 1:46:53.000
 What's the purpose of this?

1:46:53.000 --> 1:46:58.560
 If the purpose is simply self aggrandizement, then you should rethink, because it'll just

1:46:58.560 --> 1:47:01.280
 end up being a hollow life.

1:47:01.280 --> 1:47:05.200
 All of us will be forgotten in the end.

1:47:05.200 --> 1:47:08.680
 Focus protection, the idea, the policy.

1:47:08.680 --> 1:47:09.680
 What is focus protection?

1:47:09.680 --> 1:47:10.680
 Right.

1:47:10.680 --> 1:47:13.200
 So, I was saying that there's two scientific bases, right?

1:47:13.200 --> 1:47:17.120
 So one is this steep age gradient, and the second is the existence of locked arms.

1:47:17.120 --> 1:47:22.480
 Again, I think there's not very little disagreement, and the scientific can be both of those facts.

1:47:22.480 --> 1:47:28.440
 If you put those facts together, the obvious policy is to protect the people who are at

1:47:28.440 --> 1:47:33.200
 the most severe risk from the disease itself, and that's the idea of focus protection.

1:47:33.200 --> 1:47:35.280
 That's the general principle of it.

1:47:35.280 --> 1:47:40.280
 The actual implementation of it depends on the living circumstances of the people that

1:47:40.280 --> 1:47:47.080
 are at risk, the resources that are available in the community, the technology that's available

1:47:47.080 --> 1:47:49.600
 to do this.

1:47:49.600 --> 1:47:54.360
 And so it's almost always going to be, in fact, it'll always be a local thing, because

1:47:54.360 --> 1:48:00.560
 it'll depend on all of those things which are all local in nature, right?

1:48:00.560 --> 1:48:06.640
 So one very, very obvious thing in a country like ours, where so many older people live

1:48:06.640 --> 1:48:12.520
 in institutionalized settings, in nursing home settings, and that's where older, really

1:48:12.520 --> 1:48:17.960
 vulnerable, chronically ill patients often live, and you know this disease affects that

1:48:17.960 --> 1:48:23.760
 group most commonly, it is absolutely vital to protect that group.

1:48:23.760 --> 1:48:30.480
 We should have known that in February 2020 from just from the Chinese data.

1:48:30.480 --> 1:48:38.120
 And we should have thought about that group as the key constraint in our policymaking.

1:48:38.120 --> 1:48:45.320
 Instead, we thought about in February and March 2020 as hospital beds as the key constraint.

1:48:45.320 --> 1:48:52.320
 Hospital beds and ventilator shortages, and so we ran around trying to address that constraint,

1:48:52.320 --> 1:48:55.760
 like a linear programming problem, you figure out which constraint is binding and you address

1:48:55.760 --> 1:48:58.920
 that one thing and you go on to the next one, right?

1:48:58.920 --> 1:49:04.600
 If that one constraint, we said, okay, the constraint is hospital beds.

1:49:04.600 --> 1:49:11.040
 That led to the decision in many of the Northeast states to send COVID infected patients who

1:49:11.040 --> 1:49:17.400
 were on the verge of, or looked like they were about to recover, back to nursing homes,

1:49:17.400 --> 1:49:20.600
 who then spread the disease all through there, because they wanted to preserve the hospital

1:49:20.600 --> 1:49:21.600
 beds.

1:49:21.600 --> 1:49:28.200
 Well, for somebody who loves numerical optimization, I love the way you frame this.

1:49:28.200 --> 1:49:30.480
 But those are kind of connected, right?

1:49:30.480 --> 1:49:38.560
 If you actually focus on protecting the vulnerable, you will also have the effect of not hitting

1:49:38.560 --> 1:49:41.000
 the ceiling of the available hospital beds.

1:49:41.000 --> 1:49:42.000
 That's the irony.

1:49:42.000 --> 1:49:47.240
 If we protected the vulnerable, the vulnerable are the most likely to be hospitalized.

1:49:47.240 --> 1:49:52.040
 And so by protecting the hospital, by protecting the vulnerable, we would also have addressed

1:49:52.040 --> 1:49:53.920
 the shortage of hospital beds more effectively.

1:49:53.920 --> 1:49:57.480
 So that little shift in priority would have had a big impact.

1:49:57.480 --> 1:50:03.920
 Okay, but specifically, the idea is to, and we can talk about different ideas of how to

1:50:03.920 --> 1:50:11.600
 actually do this, but you basically do a lockdown or something like that on a very small set

1:50:11.600 --> 1:50:12.600
 of people.

1:50:12.600 --> 1:50:15.840
 I mean, you may have to do that if its community spread is very high, but generally, I think

1:50:15.840 --> 1:50:20.520
 it would depend on, again, the living circumstances.

1:50:20.520 --> 1:50:25.680
 So for instance, if you are in a, if you have a, here's a very simple idea that doesn't

1:50:25.680 --> 1:50:30.120
 require a lockdown forced on them, I don't actually generally, I'm not in favor of that

1:50:30.120 --> 1:50:34.080
 kind of forced lockdown because you just won't get cooperation.

1:50:34.080 --> 1:50:38.120
 But what you could do is provide resources to that group of people.

1:50:38.120 --> 1:50:44.960
 So imagine you live next door to somebody, an older couple, and there's high community

1:50:44.960 --> 1:50:45.960
 spread.

1:50:45.960 --> 1:50:49.040
 Well, they have to go grocery shopping.

1:50:49.040 --> 1:50:53.880
 We did like some of these, some communities did these like senior only grocery hour, right?

1:50:53.880 --> 1:50:57.500
 But they have to still have to go out and they might get exposed in when they're shopping

1:50:57.500 --> 1:50:59.000
 amongst other seniors.

1:50:59.000 --> 1:51:03.480
 Well, why not organize home delivery of groceries to them?

1:51:03.480 --> 1:51:06.720
 We did that for the laptop class, right?

1:51:06.720 --> 1:51:10.160
 Or it can even just as a volunteer effort, you know, the older people living next door

1:51:10.160 --> 1:51:13.600
 just call them up and say, can I help you get, go out and go shopping for you.

1:51:13.600 --> 1:51:17.280
 And so you would have potentially federal support of that kind of thing.

1:51:17.280 --> 1:51:19.320
 So these kinds of efforts.

1:51:19.320 --> 1:51:22.320
 And identify where the vulnerable people live.

1:51:22.320 --> 1:51:25.720
 It's really challenging in multi generational homes, LA County, for instance, there's a

1:51:25.720 --> 1:51:32.480
 lot of older people living together with younger people in relatively crowded, they're there.

1:51:32.480 --> 1:51:35.840
 It's really quite a challenge, but there again, you can use resources.

1:51:35.840 --> 1:51:42.160
 So if grandma is worried that grandson has come home, but is potentially being exposed,

1:51:42.160 --> 1:51:45.480
 grandson calls grandma says, I mean, I might have been at a party where I might do that

1:51:45.480 --> 1:51:50.040
 where COVID was grandma calls public health, public health then says, okay, you can have

1:51:50.040 --> 1:51:54.440
 this hotel room for a couple of days until you check to turn negative.

1:51:54.440 --> 1:52:02.120
 In case it wasn't clear, the idea of focus protection is the people that are vulnerable

1:52:02.120 --> 1:52:08.400
 protect them and everybody else goes on with their lives, open up the economy, just do

1:52:08.400 --> 1:52:09.400
 as it was before.

1:52:09.400 --> 1:52:13.240
 And there was still fear abroad, so there still would be some restrictions people would

1:52:13.240 --> 1:52:16.840
 pose on themselves, they probably would go to parties less, the grandsons probably wouldn't

1:52:16.840 --> 1:52:19.480
 go so many parties, right?

1:52:19.480 --> 1:52:23.640
 There would be less participation in big gatherings.

1:52:23.640 --> 1:52:27.720
 You may even say like big gatherings in order to restrict community spread again, I'm not

1:52:27.720 --> 1:52:29.600
 against any of that.

1:52:29.600 --> 1:52:34.080
 But you shouldn't be closing businesses, you shouldn't be closing churches and synagogues,

1:52:34.080 --> 1:52:38.640
 you shouldn't be closing, you shouldn't be forcing people to not go to school.

1:52:38.640 --> 1:52:45.000
 You should not be shuttering businesses, you should just allow society to go on, some disease

1:52:45.000 --> 1:52:46.000
 will spread.

1:52:46.000 --> 1:52:49.800
 But as we've seen, the lockdown didn't stop the disease from spreading anyways.

1:52:49.800 --> 1:52:50.960
 Right.

1:52:50.960 --> 1:52:58.800
 So what do you make of the criticism that this idea like all good ideas cannot actually

1:52:58.800 --> 1:53:03.560
 be implemented in a heterogeneous society where there's a lot of people intermixing

1:53:03.560 --> 1:53:10.120
 and once you open it up, people like the younger people will just forget that this is even

1:53:10.120 --> 1:53:14.520
 existing and they'll stop caring about the older people and mess up the whole thing and

1:53:14.520 --> 1:53:16.920
 the government will not want to fund.

1:53:16.920 --> 1:53:20.840
 And you kind of the great efforts you're talking about about food delivery and then food delivery

1:53:20.840 --> 1:53:24.720
 services, be like, why the heck am I helping out on this anyway?

1:53:24.720 --> 1:53:26.960
 Because like it's not making me much money.

1:53:26.960 --> 1:53:30.640
 And so therefore like all good ideas, it will collapse.

1:53:30.640 --> 1:53:31.640
 That might be true.

1:53:31.640 --> 1:53:34.080
 But I think it's always a risk with policy.

1:53:34.080 --> 1:53:39.600
 But I think back to the moment, we actually felt like we were in this together to some

1:53:39.600 --> 1:53:40.600
 extent.

1:53:40.600 --> 1:53:41.600
 Yes.

1:53:41.600 --> 1:53:42.600
 Right.

1:53:42.600 --> 1:53:49.160
 I think that that empathy that we had that was used to like tell people to stay in and

1:53:49.160 --> 1:53:55.880
 like happily, not really happily, but like stay in to like wear a mask or to do all these

1:53:55.880 --> 1:54:00.880
 things that we thought would help other people could have been redirected to actually helping

1:54:00.880 --> 1:54:02.920
 the people who most needed to be helped.

1:54:02.920 --> 1:54:11.200
 Especially, I do remember March, so this is even way before Barrington, all that kind

1:54:11.200 --> 1:54:19.960
 of stuff, March, April, May, there was a feeling like if we all just work together, we'll solve

1:54:19.960 --> 1:54:20.960
 this.

1:54:20.960 --> 1:54:21.960
 Right.

1:54:21.960 --> 1:54:24.280
 And that may be started to, when did that start breaking down?

1:54:24.280 --> 1:54:31.040
 I mean, unfortunately, the election is mixed into this, that it became politicized.

1:54:31.040 --> 1:54:32.880
 But I think it lasted quite a long time.

1:54:32.880 --> 1:54:37.640
 I think into the summer, I think there was some of that sense, I don't know, obviously

1:54:37.640 --> 1:54:42.560
 varied among different people, but I think that it's true, it would have been challenging.

1:54:42.560 --> 1:54:47.000
 It's also true that it's heterogeneous, exactly the way you said.

1:54:47.000 --> 1:54:50.760
 But what that means is you need a local response, a response.

1:54:50.760 --> 1:54:57.040
 Also like my vision of a public health officer is someone that understands their community,

1:54:57.040 --> 1:55:01.320
 not necessarily the nation at large, but their community, and then works within their community

1:55:01.320 --> 1:55:07.040
 to figure out how to deploy the resources that are available to do the kind of protection

1:55:07.040 --> 1:55:08.640
 policies we're talking about.

1:55:08.640 --> 1:55:10.120
 That's what should have happened.

1:55:10.120 --> 1:55:15.960
 Instead, they spent a huge amount of efforts closing, making sure businesses stayed closed.

1:55:15.960 --> 1:55:21.000
 Things that, I mean, there are like hardware stores that closed.

1:55:21.000 --> 1:55:25.080
 What good did closing a hardware store do for the spread of COVID?

1:55:25.080 --> 1:55:28.440
 If it had an effect on spread, COVID spread, I mean, it's going to be more checking to

1:55:28.440 --> 1:55:33.200
 make sure that Plexiglas was put up everywhere, which now in retrospect turns out to probably

1:55:33.200 --> 1:55:37.680
 made the disease worse.

1:55:37.680 --> 1:55:42.420
 Masking enforcement, so shaming around mask, I mean, a huge amount of effort on things

1:55:42.420 --> 1:55:47.160
 that were only tangentially related to focus protection.

1:55:47.160 --> 1:55:53.760
 What if we turned our energy, that enormous energy put into that, instead into focus protection

1:55:53.760 --> 1:55:54.760
 of the vulnerable?

1:55:54.760 --> 1:55:57.280
 That's essentially the conversation I was calling for.

1:55:57.280 --> 1:56:00.960
 And it wasn't, I mean, I didn't think of it as we had every single idea.

1:56:00.960 --> 1:56:05.720
 I mean, we gave some concrete proposals, but the criticism we got was that those concrete

1:56:05.720 --> 1:56:08.320
 proposals weren't enough.

1:56:08.320 --> 1:56:10.280
 And the answer to that is that's true.

1:56:10.280 --> 1:56:11.280
 They weren't enough.

1:56:11.280 --> 1:56:12.640
 I wasn't thinking of them as enough.

