2:14:27.320 --> 2:14:33.440
 And to young people looking to say that have some gifts or desire for this area, I'd say,

2:14:33.440 --> 2:14:36.240
 go for it, do what you can.

2:14:36.240 --> 2:14:37.720
 So, this area of science broadly.

2:14:37.720 --> 2:14:38.720
 Yeah.

2:14:38.720 --> 2:14:46.520
 I mean, I don't have any gifts in AI, but in health or in medicine or whatever, whatever

2:14:46.520 --> 2:14:50.200
 your gifts lie, develop them, work hard and develop them because it's worth it.

2:14:50.200 --> 2:14:57.200
 It's worth it not just because you get some status or because the journey is fun and the

2:14:57.200 --> 2:15:00.680
 result is improvements to the lives of so many.

2:15:00.680 --> 2:15:03.480
 So, I think that is the encouragement I give.

2:15:03.480 --> 2:15:09.280
 I'd also say, if you're looking at this ugliness of this debate that's happened over the pandemic,

2:15:09.280 --> 2:15:14.040
 I'd say to young people, we need you to come in and help transform it.

2:15:14.040 --> 2:15:18.440
 Many of the people who've seen this debate that behave poorly, I ask you forgive them.

2:15:18.440 --> 2:15:26.600
 I've done my best to try because many of them are acting out of their own sense that they

2:15:26.600 --> 2:15:32.600
 need to do good, but the mistake they've made is in this arrogance and this power.

2:15:32.600 --> 2:15:37.080
 When you come in, remember that example as a negative example and so that when you join

2:15:37.080 --> 2:15:42.600
 the debate, you'll join it in a spirit of humility, in a spirit of trying to learn while

2:15:42.600 --> 2:15:48.560
 keeping that love that led you to enter the field in the first place.

2:15:48.560 --> 2:15:54.600
 And yeah, choose forgiveness versus like derision.

2:15:54.600 --> 2:16:01.880
 Like the people that have messed up, give them a pass because it feels like that's how

2:16:01.880 --> 2:16:02.880
 improvement starts.

2:16:02.880 --> 2:16:07.000
 Funny, I've been thinking this is like, I told you I'm Christian, right?

2:16:07.000 --> 2:16:12.320
 So, like God has given me many opportunities to forgive people, learned to practice how

2:16:12.320 --> 2:16:13.320
 to do that.

2:16:13.320 --> 2:16:14.320
 Gave you a gift.

2:16:14.320 --> 2:16:15.640
 It's a very humbling thing, I guess.

2:16:15.640 --> 2:16:21.840
 Is there a memory from when you were young that was very formative to you?

2:16:21.840 --> 2:16:24.640
 So, you just gave advice to some young people.

2:16:24.640 --> 2:16:32.200
 Is there something that stands out to you that a decision you made, an event that happened

2:16:32.200 --> 2:16:35.480
 that made you the man you are today?

2:16:35.480 --> 2:16:38.280
 I actually grew up in a relatively poor environment.

2:16:38.280 --> 2:16:42.800
 Like I was born in India and I moved when I was four.

2:16:42.800 --> 2:16:48.600
 My dad had eight brothers and sisters and my mom had four brothers and sisters.

2:16:48.600 --> 2:16:52.120
 She grew up in the slum in Calcutta.

2:16:52.120 --> 2:16:56.880
 My dad, his dad died when he was young and he supported his family, his brothers and

2:16:56.880 --> 2:16:59.320
 sisters with the university scholarship money.

2:16:59.320 --> 2:17:04.280
 Came to the U.S. and my dad worked in a McDonald's even though he's an electrical engineer, couldn't

2:17:04.280 --> 2:17:06.800
 find a job in 1971.

2:17:06.800 --> 2:17:09.360
 And so, he worked at McDonald's.

2:17:09.360 --> 2:17:17.240
 We lived in a, like this, basically the housing port like development in Cambridge, just like

2:17:17.240 --> 2:17:21.640
 this middle building on the 17th floor of this housing development.

2:17:21.640 --> 2:17:25.000
 I mean, I think that was transformative for me.

2:17:25.000 --> 2:17:31.800
 Like, I didn't realize so much at the time how that experience of being essentially like

2:17:31.800 --> 2:17:36.440
 poor, lower middle class, what effect it had on my outlook.

2:17:36.440 --> 2:17:40.760
 You mentioned to me offline that you listened to a conversation that I had with my dad.

2:17:40.760 --> 2:17:42.800
 What impact did your dad have on your life?

2:17:42.800 --> 2:17:45.160
 What memories do you have about him?

2:17:45.160 --> 2:17:47.720
 He was a rocket scientist, actually.

2:17:47.720 --> 2:17:50.920
 He helped design rocket guidance systems.

2:17:50.920 --> 2:17:55.440
 He died when I was 20 and I still miss him to this day.

2:17:55.440 --> 2:18:04.520
 And I think that experience of seeing him sacrifice himself for his family, a brilliant

2:18:04.520 --> 2:18:09.600
 man, but in many ways frustrated with like the, his opportunities in the world was partly

2:18:09.600 --> 2:18:13.040
 what led him to come to the U.S. in the first place.

2:18:13.040 --> 2:18:16.320
 That's transformed, that's had a transformative effect on me.

2:18:16.320 --> 2:18:21.760
 And I wish I could tell him that looking back.

2:18:21.760 --> 2:18:25.360
 Do you think about your own mortality?

2:18:25.360 --> 2:18:27.040
 Do you think about your death?

2:18:27.040 --> 2:18:29.560
 Your dad is no longer with us.

2:18:29.560 --> 2:18:34.160
 You're the old wise sage that represents.

2:18:34.160 --> 2:18:40.160
 I feel like it's funny that I've only worried about death once in this pandemic, although

2:18:40.160 --> 2:18:47.320
 I've had two of my cousins who's 73 and my uncle who's 74 die in India during the pandemic

2:18:47.320 --> 2:18:52.920
 and I grieve them, both from COVID.

2:18:52.920 --> 2:18:57.440
 Like the fear of COVID really has only hit me only really once during this.

2:18:57.440 --> 2:18:59.440
 It wasn't from me.

2:18:59.440 --> 2:19:01.200
 And I recognize it as irrational.

2:19:01.200 --> 2:19:07.880
 So on the eve of the Santa Clara County seroprevalence study, it was a really interesting thing

2:19:07.880 --> 2:19:11.440
 because so many people volunteered to help.

2:19:11.440 --> 2:19:18.120
 And my daughter, who's 20, I guess was 19 at the time and my wife also volunteered to

2:19:18.120 --> 2:19:21.160
 help with like various aspects of the study.

2:19:21.160 --> 2:19:24.240
 And so the eve of the study, they were going to go out in public.

2:19:24.240 --> 2:19:28.080
 And I didn't know what the death rate was because we hadn't done the study.

2:19:28.080 --> 2:19:31.680
 And I suspected it was lower than people were saying, but I didn't know.

2:19:31.680 --> 2:19:37.080
 I knew about the age gradient because I'd seen the Chinese data and my daughter's young,

2:19:37.080 --> 2:19:41.120
 but my wife is my age and I didn't know the death rate.

2:19:41.120 --> 2:19:43.720
 And I couldn't sleep the night before.

2:19:43.720 --> 2:19:49.480
 Like what if I'm putting my family, my kid, my daughter and my wife at risk because of

2:19:49.480 --> 2:19:52.280
 some activity that I'm doing.

2:19:52.280 --> 2:19:53.280
 It was kind of, I don't know.

2:19:53.280 --> 2:19:54.280
 I mean, it was actually.

2:19:54.280 --> 2:20:00.480
 So it was worried about the well being and of others when you look in the mirror.

2:20:00.480 --> 2:20:01.480
 If I die, I die.

2:20:01.480 --> 2:20:06.320
 I mean, like I just, it's not, again, I'm Christian, so I don't, death is not the end for me.

2:20:06.320 --> 2:20:07.320
 I believe.

2:20:07.320 --> 2:20:13.680
 And so I don't, I don't particularly worried about my own death, but I do, I mean, I just,

2:20:13.680 --> 2:20:17.680
 I think we can't help but worry about the well being of our loved ones.

2:20:17.680 --> 2:20:24.320
 So from the perspective of God, then let me ask you, what do you think is the meaning

2:20:24.320 --> 2:20:25.800
 of this whole journey we're on?

2:20:25.800 --> 2:20:27.520
 What do you think is the meaning of life?

2:20:27.520 --> 2:20:29.280
 No, it's very simple.

2:20:29.280 --> 2:20:30.280
 Love one another.

2:20:30.280 --> 2:20:32.680
 Treat your neighbor as yourself.

2:20:32.680 --> 2:20:33.680
 It's love.

2:20:33.680 --> 2:20:34.680
 Yeah.

2:20:34.680 --> 2:20:35.680
 As simple as that.

2:20:35.680 --> 2:20:40.080
 Well, I'd love to see a little bit more of that in this pandemic.

2:20:40.080 --> 2:20:44.440
 It's an opportunity for the best of our nature to shine.

2:20:44.440 --> 2:20:50.000
 It's, I've seen some of the worst, but I think some of that is just good therapy.

2:20:50.000 --> 2:20:55.040
 And I'm hoping in the end, what we have here is, is love.

2:20:55.040 --> 2:21:01.560
 At the very least, make your dad proud with some incredible rockets that we're launching

2:21:01.560 --> 2:21:02.560
 out there.

2:21:02.560 --> 2:21:04.520
 I think you get along well with my dad, Lex.

2:21:04.520 --> 2:21:06.080
 I definitely would.

2:21:06.080 --> 2:21:07.080
 Thank you so much.

2:21:07.080 --> 2:21:08.960
 This is an incredible honor to talk to you, Jay.

2:21:08.960 --> 2:21:13.520
 You've been an inspiration to so many people and keep fighting the good fight.

2:21:13.520 --> 2:21:16.200
 Thank you so much for spending your valuable time with me today.

2:21:16.200 --> 2:21:17.200
 Thank you for having me here.

2:21:17.200 --> 2:21:18.700
 I appreciate it.

